  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>What is the Pelvic Floor?</h1>
      <p>Understanding the hidden muscles that control bladder, bowel, and sexual function, and how to keep them healthy.</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Anatomy of the Pelvic Floor</h2>
      <p>The pelvic floor is a group of muscles, ligaments, and connective tissues that form a "sling" or "hammock" at the base of your pelvis. It stretches from the pubic bone at the front to the tailbone at the back, and side-to-side between the sitting bones.</p>

      <p>These muscles act as the foundation for your core and have several critical functions:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Support:</strong> They hold up the pelvic organs, including the bladder, uterus (in females), prostate (in males), and rectum.</li>
        <li><strong>Sphincter Control:</strong> They wrap around the urethra and rectum to help control the release of urine and feces, preventing incontinence.</li>
        <li><strong>Sexual Function:</strong> In people with vaginas, these muscles contract during orgasm. In people with penises, they are involved in achieving and maintaining an erection.</li>
        <li><strong>Stability:</strong> They work with your deep abdominal and back muscles to stabilize your spine and pelvis.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Understanding Pelvic Floor Dysfunction</h2>
      <p>Pelvic floor dysfunction occurs when you are unable to control the muscles of your pelvic floor effectively. This usually falls into two categories: the muscles are either too weak (hypotonic) or too tight (hypertonic).</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Hypotonic (Weak) Pelvic Floor</h3>
        <p>A weak pelvic floor struggles to support the organs or maintain sphincter control. This is common after childbirth, surgery, or simply as part of aging.</p>
        <p><strong>Symptoms include:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Urinary or fecal incontinence (leaking).</li>
          <li>Pelvic organ prolapse (a feeling of heaviness or bulging in the vagina).</li>
          <li>Reduced sensation during sexual intercourse.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Hypertonic (Tight) Pelvic Floor</h3>
        <p>A hypertonic pelvic floor means the muscles are constantly in spasm or tension and cannot relax. Doing Kegels can actually make this worse.</p>
        <p><strong>Symptoms include:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Pelvic pain or pain in the lower back or hips.</li>
          <li>Pain during sexual intercourse (dyspareunia).</li>
          <li>Difficulty urinating or a slow urine stream.</li>
          <li>Constipation or straining during bowel movements.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Treatment and Seeking Help</h2>
      <p>The gold standard for treating pelvic floor dysfunction is seeing a <strong>Pelvic Floor Physical Therapist (PFPT)</strong>. A PFPT is specially trained to assess whether your muscles are too tight, too weak, or uncoordinated.</p>

      <p>Depending on your diagnosis, treatment may involve:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Strengthening Exercises:</strong> Such as Kegels, but taught correctly and only if the muscles are weak.</li>
        <li><strong>Relaxation Techniques:</strong> Diaphragmatic breathing and stretches to release tension in a hypertonic pelvic floor.</li>
        <li><strong>Manual Therapy:</strong> Internal or external massage to release trigger points in the muscles.</li>
        <li><strong>Biofeedback:</strong> Using sensors to help you become more aware of how to contract and relax the muscles properly.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you are experiencing any symptoms of pelvic floor dysfunction, do not assume it is just "normal" or something you have to live with. Seek an evaluation from a qualified professional.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="card">
      <h3>Explore Related Topics</h3>
      <p>The health of your pelvic floor is closely tied to other aspects of sexual well-being:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/sexual-health-glossary">The Complete Sexual Health Glossary</a> - Return to our main pillar page.</li>
        <li><a href="/what-is-vaginismus">What is Vaginismus?</a> - Learn about a specific condition involving involuntary pelvic floor muscle spasms.</li>
        <li><a href="/what-is-erectile-dysfunction">What is Erectile Dysfunction?</a> - Understand how pelvic floor muscles play a role in maintaining erections.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-container">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h4>What are the signs of a weak pelvic floor?</h4>
          <p>Signs of a weak pelvic floor include urinary or fecal incontinence (especially when coughing, sneezing, or exercising), a feeling of heaviness or bulging in the vagina or rectum (prolapse), and reduced sensation during sex.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h4>Are Kegels always the right answer for pelvic floor issues?</h4>
          <p>No. While Kegels can strengthen a weak pelvic floor, they can actually worsen symptoms if your pelvic floor muscles are hypertonic (too tight). It is important to see a pelvic floor physical therapist for a proper diagnosis before starting an exercise regimen.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h4>What is a hypertonic pelvic floor?</h4>
          <p>A hypertonic pelvic floor occurs when the muscles in the pelvic floor are too tense and are unable to relax. This can cause pelvic pain, pain during sex, constipation, and frequent urination.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
